  "материалы__PreciousMetalsQuarterly2012SepExecSum::p1::c0": {
    "chunk": {
      "chunk_id": "материалы__PreciousMetalsQuarterly2012SepExecSum::p1::c0",
      "doc_id": "материалы__PreciousMetalsQuarterly2012SepExecSum",
      "source": "/content/drive/MyDrive/minekg/raw/материалы/PreciousMetalsQuarterly2012SepExecSum.pdf",
      "page": 1,
      "lang": "en",
      "text": "Precious Metals Quarterly 2012 Q3 CRU International Limited confidential Executive summary Silver: prices will remain strong until 2015 Although the ebb and flow in ETF holdings are no longer providing a demonstrable guide to investors’ desire to buy, our tabulations show that a fundamental surplus of 5,500-6,000 t/y is being generated without putting any immense downward pressure on silver’s price. This latent demand will hold until monetary policy is tightened in 2015. Silver will then fall to $15/oz. • After bouncing back in 2010, fabrication demand has slipped once again in 2011-12. It is forecast to grow at 3-3.5% p.a. in 2013-15 but weaker coinage will be a drag beyond then. • Subject to financing being available, project development would largely be unencumbered at today’s prices. However, mine supply will be curtailed in 2016-17 once prices have fallen. • Even though fabrication demand will struggle to grow in 2016-17 as coinage offtake falls, the price-induced curtailments will rein in mine supply by more and cut the market’s surplus to around 3,000 tonnes in 2017. The stock-to-consumption ratio will then be 2.5-2.6 years.",
      "doc_type": "материалы",
      "path_year": 2012,
      "path_geo": null,
      "meta_year": 2012
    },
    "extraction": {
